Anonymous Sun 28 Oct 2018 18:19:07 No.19086647 Report
Quoted By: >>19086862 >>19087052 >>19087932 >>19088750 >>19095456 >>19102073
Hey, it's Ago! Here is the final update to this installment of Anan and Emmas' story. Thank you so much for reading it all the way through, and if you haven't -- well, it's finished! No more having to wait for updates! As usual, I love feedback, good or bad!

https://pastebin.com/2kkkNe7r

The Epilogue starts on line 2420. Given how short the chapter is, I'll forego posting an excerpt and instead let you guys in on something else: this story was almost something much, MUCH different.

It was originally going to be the aftermath of high fantasy. In Chapter 6, where Emmas is recounting dragon history to Anan, she mentions the human settlements of Jagutun and Gandameid. Originally, these were going to be cities belonging to the Kobolds and Dwarves, respectively. The Kobolds had been culturally uplifted by Dragons and created an enormous gleaming city of gold. Dwarves in Jagutun were content to mine and trade, as is the stereotype. Both races enjoyed minor magical abilities that made their own lives slightly easier, but nothing as powerful as Dragon abilities.

The dragons would have wiped out not barbarians, but orcs in the southern swamplands!

From here things would have played out mostly the same. Fearful of their human neighbors, Kobolds and Dwarves deserted their cities to lands unknown, and whatever magic they had went with them.

As I was about 6000 words into the chapter, I realized holy fuck, this is literally the opening to Shrek, just ratcheted up a few magnitudes. Humans chase away the magical creatures and the land after they leave is boring and sterile. As I thought about it more, I realized having more magical creatures took away a bit of Emmas' spotlight, and thus made the relationship she and Anan shared seem smaller in comparison to how the rest of the world used to be. So you have the story as it is now.
